  <title>Exploring Fractions</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
For each of the following explorations, keep in mind how you might explain your process.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Area Model Representations
      </p>
      <ol type="a">
        <li>
          If the following rectangle is one whole, show two-thirds.
          <sidebyside width="40%">
            <image source="images/generic-rectangle.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
        <li>
          If the following rectangle is one whole, show five-thirds.
          <sidebyside width="40%">
            <image source="images/generic-rectangle.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
        <li>
          If the following rectangle is three-fourths, draw one whole.
          <sidebyside width="30%">
            <image source="images/generic-square.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
        <li>
          If this rectangle is four-thirds, show what rectangle could be the whole.
          <sidebyside width="40%">
            <image source="images/generic-rectangle.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
        <li>Maria says that the shaded region below represents the fraction <m> \frac{9}{12} </m>. Carmina says the shaded region represents the fraction <m> \frac{9}{4} </m>. Explain why each of the two studentâ€™s answers can be considered correct.
          <sidebyside width="50%">
            <image source="images/nine-fourths-vs-twelfths.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Set Model Representations
      </p>
      <ol type="a">
        <li>
          If 14 counters are one whole, shade the counters that make three-sevenths.
          <sidebyside width="30%">
            <image source="images/fourteen-counters.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
        <li>
          Draw 12 counters like part a. If 12 counters are one whole, how many are in five-thirds of a set?
        </li>
        <li>
          Draw 21 coutners. If 21 counters are three-fifths of a set, how many counters are in the full set (1 whole)?
        </li>
        <li>
          Draw 12 counters. If 12 counters are three-halves of a set, how many counters are in one set (1 whole)?
        </li>
        <li>
          What fraction of this set is shaded in?
          <sidebyside width="30%">
            <image source="images/counters-one-third.png"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <pagebreak />

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Cuisenaire Rods (Online Cuisenaire Rods: http:///nrich.maths.org/4348)
      </p>
      <ol type="a">
        <li>
          Select a brown Cuisenaire Rod.  If brown is the whole, which rod is one-fourth?
        </li>
        <li>
          If dark green is the whole, what rod represents two-thirds? What rod represents three-halves?
        </li>
        <li>
          Select a dark green Cuisenaire Rod.  If dark green is two-thirds, what rod is the whole?
        </li>
        <li>
          Select a yellow Cuisenaire Rod.  If yellow is five-fourths, what rod is one whole? What rod is 2?
        </li>
        <li>
          Select a dark green Cuisenaire Rod.  If dark green is the whole, what fraction is the yellow rod?
        </li>
        <li>
          If the brown rod is one whole, what fraction is the orange rod?
        </li>
        <li>
          If the blue rod is 3, what rod represents <m> \frac{2}{3} </m>?
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Pattern Blocks Representation (yellow hexagon, blue parallelogram, red trapezoid, and green triangle)
      (Online Pattern Blocks: http://www.mathplayground.com/patternblocks.html)
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If the yellow hexagon represents one whole:
      </p>
      <ol type="a">
          <li>
              What shape would represent <m> \frac{1}{2} </m> ?
          </li>
          <li>
              What shape would represent <m> \frac{1}{3} </m> ?
          </li>
          <li>
              What shape would represent <m> \frac{1}{6} </m> ?
          </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If the blue parallelogram represents one whole:
      </p>
      <ol type="a">
        <li>
          What fraction would the red trapezoid represent?
        </li>
        <li>
          What fraction would the green triangle represent?
        </li>
        <li>
          What fraction would the yellow hexagon represent?
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If the double hexagon represents one whole:
      </p>
      <ol type="a">
        <li>
          What fraction would the red trapezoid represent?
        </li>
        <li>
          What fraction would the green triangle represent?
        </li>
        <li>
          What fraction would the yellow hexagon represent?
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
